## The Entity ID system clusters similar creatives together

Andromeda uses an internal identifier called **Entity ID** that groups creatives the platform considers visually or thematically similar, even when they have different Creative IDs. This means 50 similar ad variations effectively count as **one "ticket" to the auction**.

Detection methods include computer vision analyzing pixels, composition, colors, and frame structures; NLP processing ad copy and text overlays; audio analysis for video ads; and structural similarity assessment of text placement, button positioning, and overlay structures. The first **3 seconds of video carry disproportionate weight** in similarity detection.

What gets clustered as "the same":
- Same image with different headlines → clustered together
- Videos with similar opening sequences
- Ads with identical layouts but different underlying photos
- Minor text/color changes on same visual structure
- Same visual rhythm and opening style in video mashups

Jon Loomer's insight captures this perfectly: "If you make 100 static ad images that all look similar in the eyes of Meta, you have made ONE ad."

