## Post-Andromeda failures trace to old structures and similar creatives

The most common failure pattern: advertisers continuing with fragmented campaigns, micro-budgets, and the now-obsolete **3:2:2 testing method** (3 hooks on same video). This approach "leaves campaigns looking identical to the algorithm. Andromeda recognizes these as duplicates and often suppresses delivery before they scale."

**Case study: Clean-eez (Smart Marketer Agency)**
The brand's performance tanked in August 2025 with increased CPMs, CPCs, and CPAs. Cause: 8 separate campaigns fragmenting data, lack of creative diversity, and budget spread too thin. The recovery involved consolidating to 2 campaigns, loading every strong ad from the past year (including "fatigued" creatives), and diversifying styles. Results: **CPMs dropped 20%, CPAs dropped 35% within days**.

**Case study: Karina Gardner (Design Bootcamp)**
Costs spiked to $86 per conversion post-update due to insufficient creative diversity. After adding 8 genuinely new creatives (carousel, images, AI iterations), cost per conversion dropped to **$13.87 within 24 hours**.

Strategies that stopped working include detailed interest-based targeting ("largely obsolete—Andromeda performs best with broad, country-level targeting"), lookalike audiences as hard targeting boundaries (now only signal inputs), separate retargeting campaigns (many advertisers have stopped running them entirely), and the max 6 ads per ad set rule (Meta removed this guidance; 8-15+ now works better).

